'''"Judo" Jim Wallhead''' (born March 14, 1984) is an [[English people|English]] professional [[mixed martial arts|mixed martial artist]] who competes in the [[Welterweight (MMA)|welterweight]] division. A professional MMA competitor since 2005, Wallhead fought in various promotions, though predominantly in [[Cage Warriors]] before signing a contract with [[Bellator Fighting Championships]] in 2009 <ref>[http://mmajunkie.com/news/17298/top-british-fighter-jim-wallhead-signed-for-bellators-season-two-welterweight-tourney.mma Top British fighter Jim Wallhead signed for Bellator's season-two welterweight tourney]</ref>. Wallhead holds a Black Belt in [[Judo]]; was a three time Under 21 British Judo Champion and a former British Judo Youth Games Team Member.<ref>http://www.cagewarriors.com/fighter.106.htm</ref>

==Mixed martial arts==

Like fellow Team Rough House member [[Andre Winner]], Wallhead trains under Head Coach Nathan Leverton at the Leicester Shootfighters gym, where Wallhead also coaches.<ref>http://leicestermma.wordpress.com/leicester_shootfighters</ref> Wallhead also trains Muay Thai with the former Multi Time Kickboxing Champion Owen Comerie<ref>http://www.jimmywallheadmma.co.uk/biography-jimmy-wallhead-mma.htm</ref>, who previously trained Dan Hardy. Wallhead works his strength and conditioning with [http://www.fighterstrength.com/ Ollie Richardson] at the Leicester Tigers Rugby Union training ground.<ref>http://www.sherdog.com/news/press%20releases/Jim-Wallhead-To-Face-The-Brazilian-Bad-Boy-14499</ref>

Although he comes from a Judo background, Wallhead explains his fighting style as "a mix of stand up with good takedowns and strong GNP (ground-and-pound); taking the fight wherever is best for me depending on my opponent<U+2019>s weaknesses,<U+201D>. He says that his main strength is his takedown defence, which helps him control the fight.<ref>http://www.mmamadness.com/2009/08/the-new-breed-jim-wallhead/</ref>  Wallhead has also shown improving boxing and some explosive KO power in his most recent fights, most noticeably against Tom Haddock in April 2008<ref>http://www.fightersonlymagazine.co.uk/news/viewarticle.php?id=570</ref> and against the BJJ Black Belt Fabio Toldo in 2008, which was described by one of Wallhead's team mates as 'one of the worst knockouts they've seen'.<ref>http://www.fightersonlymagazine.co.uk/news/viewarticle.php?id=2432</ref>

Wallhead has also seen Title glory during his MMA career as he has previously captured the Cage Gladiators British Welterweight Title defeating the UFC veteran [[Jason Tan]]<ref>http://www.fightopinion.com/2006/09/08/cage-gladiators-2-next-generation-results/</ref>. Wallhead is also known for winning the 2h2h 2006 "Road to Japan" under 83kg Tournament, despite flying over to Holland on just 48 hours notice and fighting in a higher weight class too.<ref>http://www.ironlife.com/forum/showthread.php?t=74883</ref><ref>http://www.ironlife.com/forum/showthread.php?t=74705</ref> He is also the reigning House of Pain British Welterweight Champion and the Clash of Warriors World Welterweight Champion.<ref>http://www.loughboroughecho.net/loughborough-sport/other-sport/2009/09/11/wallhead-world-champion-after-dramatic-late-twist-73871-24649403/</ref> He was an alternate for the welterweight division on [[The Ultimate Fighter: United States vs. United Kingdom]].<ref>http://www.aroundtheoctagon.com/?p=1721</ref>

In November 2009, Wallhead scored the best win of his career when he defeated the UFC Ultimate Fighter Season 9 participant [[Che Mills]] at Knuckleup At The Manor in Newport, Wales. <ref>http://www.fightersonlymagazine.co.uk/eventreports/viewarticle.php?id=3342&offset=1</ref> That victory led to several major websites and even the British Newspaper [[The Sun (newspaper)|The Sun]] to speculate that Wallhead may be headed to the UFC. <ref>http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/sport/ufc/2710251/Jimmy-Wallhead-sends-message-to-UFC-matchmaker-Joe-Silva.html</ref>

===Bellator Fighting Championships===

However, in December 2009, Wallhead was signed by the [[Bellator Fighting Championships]] to compete in their 2010 eight man, number 1 contender Welterweight Tournament, which will kick off on April 8th 2010.<ref>http://www.bellator.com/BellatorFightingChampionshipsfiles/PressRelease41.htm</ref> Upon signing with Bellator Wallhead was quoted as saying "This is exactly what I<U+2019>ve been wanting. Let down after let down came my way but now good things are happening."<ref>http://www.mmaunltd.com/fighters/interview-details.asp/id/49/wallhead-interview-talks-bellator-fc-signing.htm</ref>

Wallhead is currently on a six fight win streak which has seen him ranked in both the UK and European top 10 rankings (4th in the UK <ref>http://www.mmaunltd.com/fighters/</ref> and 6th in Europe<ref>http://www.groundandpound.de/mma/rankings/european-top-ten/weltergewicht/</ref>).

He is currently training with the rest of the "Team Rough House" members as he prepares to make his Bellator debut at [[Bellator 15]]. Wallhead will have his first fight in the welterweight tournament against American, [[Jacob McClintock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/18097/bellator-welterweight-tourney-kicks-off-at-bellator-14-and-bellator-15-matchups-set.mma|title=Bellator welterweight tourney kicks off at Bellator 14 and Bellator 15, matchups set |accessdate=2010-02-26}}</ref>

